      "question": "Two distinct circles have radii $r_1$ and $r_2$ such that $r_1 = 2r_2$. If a sector in the first circle has a central angle of $\\theta_1 = 30^\\circ$ and a sector in the second circle has a central angle of $\\theta_2 = 120^\\circ$, what is the ratio of the area of the first sector to the area of the second sector?",
      "answer": "(B)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Recall the formula for the area of a sector: $A = \\frac{\\theta}{360^\\circ} \\times \\pi r^2$.",
          "Calculate the area of the first sector: $A_1 = \\frac{30^\\circ}{360^\\circ} \\times \\pi r_1^2 = \\frac{1}{12} \\pi (2r_2)^2 = \\frac{4}{12} \\pi r_2^2 = \\frac{1}{3} \\pi r_2^2$.",
          "Calculate the area of the second sector: $A_2 = \\frac{120^\\circ}{360^\\circ} \\times \\pi r_2^2 = \\frac{1}{3} \\pi r_2^2$.",
          "Find the ratio $\\frac{A_1}{A_2} = \\frac{\\frac{1}{3} \\pi r_2^2}{\\frac{1}{3} \\pi r_2^2} = 1:1$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$A_1 = \\frac{30}{360} \\pi (2r_2)^2 = \\frac{1}{12} \\pi (4r_2^2) = \\frac{1}{3} \\pi r_2^2 \\\\ A_2 = \\frac{120}{360} \\pi r_2^2 = \\frac{1}{3} \\pi r_2^2 \\\\ \\frac{A_1}{A_2} = \\frac{\\frac{1}{3} \\pi r_2^2}{\\frac{1}{3} \\pi r_2^2} = \\frac{1}{1}$"
      },
